Parents/Guardians:
Tomorrow (Tuesday, September 8th) and Wednesday (September 9th) we will be distributing book bags filled with important items that your child will need to start the school year! The book bags will contain curriculum materials, reading books and school supplies.

Pickup is from 9:00am until 3:00pm in the school parking lot. Families should park on the street (either Locust or Thatcher) and walk into the school yard to meet the teacher and pickup their materials. We look forward to seeing you tomorrow or Wednesday!

Also, don't forget that Red Clay is providing meal pick up in our parking lot from 11am-1pm both days! You can grab your book bag and a meal for your kids at the same time!

post_text: For the safety and well-being of all of our students, staff and families, we have made the very difficult decision to begin the 2020-2021 school year with full remote learning from home. Although, it is not ideal and we truly wish we could have the students and staff in the building and back to normal, we know that with the uncertainty of COVID-19, this is the safest and smartest choice. At this time, we expect to be fully online until (at least) October 16th. (Please see the attached letter for more information)

post_text: Sadly, due to the large spread of COVID-19 we cannot open for face to face instruction to start the school year. We will be delaying the start of the school year until Tuesday, September 8th to give us time to thoroughly plan after the governor makes his decision for all schools. At that time we will open on a hybrid schedule or full remote learning from home. Please see details in attached letter.

post_text:
Dear students and parents,

As you have witnessed over the past week, thousands of people of all races around the country and world are protesting the senseless murder of George Floyd, and the countless murders of unarmed black men and women. As a school and community, we do not promote or support violence against anyone, and do not want to see another black person die at the hands of police. As always, we stand with you in the fight against racism and any anti-Black actions or language! Black Lives Matter! We appreciate all of our teachers and staff who stand wholeheartedly in support of our students and their families, and all people of color.

If anyone is in need of support or counseling to deal with the traumatic events we have been facing, please feel free to contact the school so we can arrange those supports for you. Together as a community, we can learn to respect every person regardless of race, and promote love over hate. Keep fighting for peace and justice! We love and miss you!

As a school and community, we do not promote or support violence against anyone, and do not want to see another black person die at the hands of police. As always, we stand with you in the fight against racism and any anti-Black actions or language! Black Lives Matter! We appreciate all of our teachers and staff who stand wholeheartedly in support of our students and their families, and all people of color.

If anyone is in need of support or counseling to deal with the traumatic events we have been facing, please feel free to contact the school so we can arrange those supports for you. Together as a community, we can learn to respect every person regardless of race, and promote love over hate. Keep fighting for peace and justice! We love and miss you!

We miss our students and parents and hope everyone is staying safe during these uncertain times. Please visit our school website for additional resources to supplement the schoolwork that was sent home. If for some reason, you did not receive the work sent home for your child, please inbox us or call school on Monday. Administration will be in the Main Office.

Teachers have been working hard and preparing additional lessons for students to complete over the next several weeks. The lessons may include written assignments, books, teacher-made videos, online work, and additional resources. Schoolwork packets will be available for pickup at school on Thursday, April 2nd and Friday, April 3rd. In accordance with CDC guidelines, we will be maintaining appropriate social distances and bringing items to your cars, or to you for pickup in our school parking lot. Please feel free to contact us if you need anything and stay safe.

shared_text:
Delaware Department of Education (DDOE)
March 24, 2016 at 1:07 PM ¬∑

The National Championship Chess Team from Thomas Edison Charter School needs your help! The team, which brought home a first-place trophy in 2014 and has placed in the top five for the past four years, is raising money to take students to this year's National Chess Championship in Indianapolis next month. More than 400 students in the school play chess during the school day as part of Edison's First Move Program in the lunchroom and in the after-school program.

Secretary Godowsky had the chance to find out first-hand just how good the kids are during his visit this week!

The cost is about $1,000 per student, including transportation by coach bus, hotel, meals, and tournament fees. For many students at the school, the opportunities to travel outside of Delaware are limited, so this is a special experience for them.

Tax-deductible donations can be made here: https://www.gofundme.com/EdisonChessTeam

Bryan Townsend
May 30, 2014 at 12:28 PM ¬∑

At Thomas Edison Charter School, chess is a team sport--and a vehicle for life lessons.

Yesterday I visited Edison and was schooled in the art of chess by their award-winning chess team as I dusted off my chess technique. I first tasted defeat at the hands of Madalyn, who recently tied for 19th at the K-6 Elementary National Chess Championship in Dallas. I then held my own (but ultimately lost) in a lengthy game with Cashmere, who placed 2nd in the same tournament. I look forward to the rematches, and to additional coaching from some very savvy Edison students.

post_text:
Congrats to the Edison Chess Team! We had a great time in San Diego....and even got to visit Sea World! We're on the way home now.....

2012 Junior High National Chess Championship Awards:

Edison Team‚ÄîTied for 2nd place in the Under 750 rating section

Hodgson Team‚Äî11th place in the Under 1250 rating section (with only 2 players competing against teams of 4!)

Abu Kamara‚ÄîCo-National Champion in the Under 1250 rating section (tied for 1st place)

Ruth Ironkwe‚Äî2nd place winner in the Under 1000 rating section. She is the top female in the Nation in her section!

Jabrei Chase‚Äî5th place winner in the Under 750 rating section

Othelo Predeoux‚Äî7th place winner in the Under 750 rating section

Cashmere Young‚Äî12th place winner in the Under 750 rating section

Cameron Sheppard‚Äî17th place winner in the Under 750 rating section

Alita Robinson‚Äî20th place winner in the Under 750 rating section

The entire team did a great job and we are so proud of all of them! Thanks to our parents and staff who helped make the trip special!

post_text: Congrats to our Chess Team. They are tied for 2nd place at Nationals in San Diego! Ruth Ironkwe has not lost a game yet..she has 4 wins and just defeated the top player in the country in her section!! Cameron Sheppard, Othelo Predoux and Jabrei Chase all have 3 wins. Abu Kamara and Jayvon Davis (alumni) both have 3 wins also! One more round tonight and 2 more tomorrow!
